## THE 10 PILLARS OF ENTERPRISE DOMINATION

---

### ⚡ PILLAR 1 — DISTRIBUTED INFRASTRUCTURE OVERHAUL

**The Problem:** A single `node server/server.js` process is a single point of failure. Any memory leak, unhandled crash, or traffic spike kills everything.

#### 1.1 Process Manager → PM2 Cluster Mode
```bash
npm install -g pm2
pm2 start server/server.js -i max --name roya --exp-backoff-restart-delay=100
pm2 save && pm2 startup
```
Instantly clones your server across all CPU cores. Zero-downtime reloads with `pm2 reload roya`.

#### 1.2 Redis as the Central Nervous System
Install Redis and wire it into **4 critical systems**:

```bash
npm install ioredis connect-redis express-rate-limit-redis-store
```

**a) Distributed Rate Limiting** — Replace the current in-memory rate limiter:
```js
// server/middlewares/rateLimiter.js
const { RedisStore } = require('rate-limit-redis');
const redis = require('../config/redis'); // new config module
const loginLimiter = rateLimit({
  windowMs: 15 * 60 * 1000,
  max: 5,
  store: new RedisStore({ sendCommand: (...args) => redis.call(...args) }),
});
```
Now rate limits survive server restarts and work across ALL cluster workers.

**b) Application-Level Cache Layer** — Kill redundant DB queries:
```js
// server/config/cache.js
const redis = new Redis(config.redis.url);
const cache = {
  get: (key) => redis.get(key).then(v => v ? JSON.parse(v) : null),
  set: (key, val, ttl = 300) => redis.setex(key, ttl, JSON.stringify(val)),
  del: (key) => redis.del(key),
};
module.exports = cache;
```
Cache targets: `GET /api/services` (TTL: 5min), `GET /api/properties` (TTL: 5min), `GET /api/exhibitions` (TTL: 10min), `GET /api/admin/stats` (TTL: 60s). **This alone cuts DB load by ~70%.**

**c) Session-Based Presence** — Track online users for real-time features (Pillar 3).

**d) Job Queue Backing Store** — BullMQ requires Redis (see Pillar 4).

#### 1.3 Nginx as Reverse Proxy
```nginx
upstream roya_cluster {
    server 127.0.0.1:3000;
    # PM2 cluster handles internal load
    keepalive 64;
}

server {
    listen 443 ssl http2;
    server_name roya-advertising.com;
    
    # Brotli compression (better than gzip for text/html/JSON)
    brotli on;
    brotli_comp_level 6;
    brotli_types text/html application/json text/css application/javascript;
    
    # Static files served by Nginx (bypasses Node entirely)
    location /css/ { root /var/www/roya/client; expires 1y; add_header Cache-Control "public, immutable"; }
    location /js/  { root /var/www/roya/client; expires 1y; add_header Cache-Control "public, immutable"; }
    
    # Proxy everything else to Node
    location / {
        proxy_pass http://roya_cluster;
        proxy_http_version 1.1;
        proxy_set_header Upgrade $http_upgrade;
        proxy_set_header Connection 'upgrade';
        proxy_set_header X-Real-IP $remote_addr;
        proxy_set_header X-Forwarded-For $proxy_add_x_forwarded_for;
        proxy_cache_bypass $http_upgrade;
    }
}
```

#### 1.4 PostgreSQL Connection Pooling — PgBouncer
Your current `pg.Pool` creates up to N connections per Node process. With PM2 cluster × 4 CPUs, you now have 4 pools × 10 connections = 40 simultaneous connections. PgBouncer sits between your app and PostgreSQL in **transaction-pooling mode**, reducing actual DB connections to 5-10 while handling thousands of concurrent queries.

```
Node cluster → PgBouncer (port 6432) → PostgreSQL (port 5432)
```

